    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Richard Elman (1932-1997) was an American author, novelist and poet.  He graduated from Syracuse University in 1955 and 
	  studied creative writing at Stanford, after which he embarked on a literary career producing novels, nonfiction, essays, 
	  book reviews, poetry and other pieces.  He also worked as a journalist in Central America and taught creative writing at several 
	  institutions, including Bennington College, Columbia University, Sarah Lawrence, the University of Pennsylvania, Notre Dame, 
	  and Stony Brook University.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The <emph render="bold">Richard Elman Papers</emph> includes correspondence (1956-1992); typescript essays, 
					lectures, novels, poems, stories; and memorabilia, including financial and legal material, clippings, 
					reviews, and photographs.</p>
    </scopecontent>
